Synopsis:
Benimadhab (Biswajit Chakraborty) suspects that one of his heirs will try to murder him because he has changed his will to reduce their share. He hires Byomkesh to investigate the possible murderer, but before Byomkesh can do anything, BBenimadhab and his manservant are murdered. Byomkesh arrives at the scene of crime to find a web of deceit that he has to unravel..

Comments:
Based largely on Saradindu Bandyopadhyay's short story (Beni Sanghar), Anjan Dutta sticks largely to the original. There are some minor variations and the purist will notice them immediately, but I thought Anjan Dutt's interpretation is very plausible and does not take much away from the original story. To be honest I did not come across anything that may be called a glaring fault, except perhaps the elopement of Parag and Laboni, something that was unnecessary.
If Byomkesh is a little abrasive and Satyabati a little too strident, it is a minor quibble, for overall, Anjan Dutt tells a very satisfying tale.

Credit for that undoubtedly goes to the screenplay writer and director Anjan Dutt, but editor Arghyakamal Dutta does a very good job, as does cinematographer Indraneel Mukherjee. If the dresses are a little modern compared to the original setting, it is a minor failing. The music for the film is perhaps just a bit pedestrian.

This is a film that I unabashedly enjoyed! I'm sure you will too.


